liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Palestinians in Gaza have reported heavy air strikes in the southern city of Khan Younis, where civilians had been told to seek safety amid Israel’s bombardment of areas further north. Over a million people have been displaced in Gaza. Many heeded Israel's orders to evacuate the northern part of the sealed-off enclave on the coast of the Mediterranean Sea. Although Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu called areas in the south "safe zones" this week, Israeli military spokesman Nir Dinar said on Friday: "There are no safe zones." Some Palestinians who had fled from the north appeared to be going back because of bombings and difficult living conditions in the south, said Ravina Shamdasani, spokesperson for the UN human rights office. Gaza's overwhelmed hospitals have also been rationing their dwindling resources. Israel's defence minister said on Friday that the country's military did not plan to control "life in the Gaza Strip". AP
